ANGIOSTRONGYLIASIS & EOSINOPHILIC MENINGITIS (03)
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Angiostrongyliasis & eosinophilic meningitis 980508191641
Angiostrongyliasis & eosinophilic meningitis (02) 980509204409
[1
Date: Mon, 11 May 1998 09:53:09 -0700
From: Dr. John Walker <johnw@cidm.wh.usyd.edu.au>

There is little evidence to support the suggestion that _Angiostrongylus
cantonensis_ entered Australia after the Second World War in association
with the extension of the range of the Giant African Snail, _Achatina
fulica_.
Firstly, _A. fulica_ has only once become established in Australia, near
Cairns in northern Queensland, in the early 1970s. When detected, it was
quickly eradicated and is no longer present anywhere in the country.
Secondly, _A. cantonensis_ is very common in rats in regions of Australia
far to the south of Cairns. Its life cycle was described by Josephine
Mackerras and Dorothea Sandars in 1955 (Australian Journal of Zoology,
3(1):1-21), using parasites collected from rats caught in Brisbane.
Subsequently Manoon Bhaibulaya described a second species, _A. mackerrasae_,
also from Brisbane (Parasitology (1968) 58:789-799). In Australia these
nematodes utilise a variety of molluscs, including native land snails and
introduced slugs, as intermediate hosts. Several rodent species are
infected. _A. mackerrasae_ has only been found in _Rattus fuscipes_ (a
native species) and in the introduced _R. norvegicus_. _A. cantonensis_ has
been found in _R. norvegicus_ and _R. rattus_ - it is possible that _A.
cantonensis_ entered Australia along with these recently introduced rodents.
_A. mackerrasae_ is thought to be an indigenous species.
_A. cantonensis_ occurs at least as far south as Sydney, having been found
in dogs which died here in 1991 (Collins et al, 1991, Australian Veterinary
Journal, 69(7):170-171). _A. mackerrasae_ is probably present in Sydney as
well. I personally found a species of Angiostrongylus in _Rattus fuscipes_
collected in northern Sydney in 1969 and, although the specific identity of
those worms was not determined at the time, Bhaibulaya's observations
suggest that _A. mackerrasae_ is the only species of lung worm found in that
rat.
In view of the extended geographic range (at least 3,000 kilometres) of
these nematodes in Australia, and their documented presence well before the
only known introduction of _A. fulica_, it is most probable that they have
been present for a long time. It seems to be implicit in some of the
discussions dealing with _A. cantonensis_ that, because it was described
from rats collected in Canton, that it must have dispersed from there. At
present there is no evidence either for or against that proposition.
--
John Walker, PhD
Department of Parasitology
Centre for Infectious Diseases and Microbiology
Westmead Hospital, Westmead 2145
Australia
phone: (61-2)9845 7663
