Date: Mon, 11 May 1998 16:57:13 +1200
From: Alan Julian <juliana@mqm.govt.nz>
Source: cc'd to us when replying to <whosma@samoa.net>

Back in 1981 I was involved in looking at rat tissues from Apia [a port in
Western Samoa; - Mod.MHJ [from where 13 out of 14 had evidence of _A.
cantonensis_ infection in sections of lung and/or heart. I think the rats
were collected near the wharf.
I have copies of some papers by Joseph Alicata, which, although quite old
may be of some help to you:
Alicata,& McCarthy 1964. On the incidence and distribution of the rat
lungworm Angiostrongylus cantonensis in the Cook Islands, with observations
made in New Zealand and Western Samoa. Canadian J Zoology 42:605-611
Alicata 1964. Parasitic infections of man and animals in Hawaii. Technical
bulletin No 61 Hawaii Agricultural experiment Station
I have a reference to ...
Beck, Cardina & Alicata, 1980, Eosinophilic meningitis due to
Angiostrongylus cantonensis in American Samoa. Hawaii medical J 39:245-257.
I may have some more buried deeper in my files. This investigation was
carried out by WHO personal (Dirk Steichmann I think was one person I dealt
with, memory is a bit unclear now). There may still be some records there.
I think many species of mollusks may be involved as may the contamination of
vegetables by these mollusks.
I hope this is some help.
--
Alan Julian
Veterinary Pathologist
e-mail: juliana@mqm.govt.nz
[While this snail and WWII makes for a fascinating and instructive
epidemiological case study, one should not lose sight of the traditional
seafaring rodent. For example, rats regularly trapped and examined during
1962-75 in the port of New Orleans were negative for this parasite. But
during April 1986 to February 1987 Campbell & Little found some 20+/94
_Rattus norvegicus_ and _0+/20 R. rattus_ live-trapped in the New Orleans
wharves. Interestingly in the Audubon Zoo, close to their trapping area, a
howler monkey died in 1987 with a _A. cantonensis_ meningitis after a short
illness. Subsequently, in 1993 an 11 y.o. boy in New Orleans became ill with
myalgia after eating a raw snail on a dare; his blood test for _A.
cantonensis_ was positive. Latterly in September, 1996, we here at the LSU
Vet School were presented with a six month old miniature horse with a
history of progressive paresis ... necropsy showed an aesinophilic
meningitis and subsequently adult _A.cantonensis_ were recovered;
identification was confirmed by Mike Kinsella, U Montana. The foal had got
infected in Picayune, Mississippi; Picayune is 20 miles inland and some 60
miles NE of the area where Campbell & Little found the infected rats.
I am informed that infected rats have also been identified in South American
and West African ports. Mike Kinsella has suggested that parasitologists
near ports, both coastal & riverine, should make a habit of trapping and
examining rats for this nematode. - Mod.MHJ
....................................mhj/es
